The Southern Oasis — The Fortified Hinge

The Southern Oasis is the fortified hinge between oasis civil life and
pyramid frontier risk. Where the Northern Oasis verifies and counts, the
south arms, stages, and absorbs the cost of deeper desert ambition.

Locals summarize it with a hard proverb: 'North records; south buries.'

Sitting at a secondary fracture of the Deepwell Confluence, the Southern
Oasis was never the seat of the Water Court or the hub of the charter road
network. From the beginning it was a relay station, the last point where
the Great Oasis's administrative reach thinned to the point where local
improvisation replaced central policy.

The Bastion Wardens, a militarized water-control authority, ration under
permanent emergency doctrine. They built their institution on a single
hard lesson: when the Great Oasis refused to enforce the Twin Basin
Compact's emergency water-sharing provisions, the Southern Oasis concluded
that no external authority would save it.

The settlement processes what the pyramids produce: casualties, disputed
relics, broken expeditions. The Mortuary Circle handles the dead as a civic
function, not a religious rite. The Bazaar Syndics authenticate and tax
artifacts removed from the Southern Pyramid with provenance chains trusted
across the oasis network.

Expedition convoys are hardened here. Load distribution, casualty drills,
and thermal staging protocols are mandatory before any group departs for the
Southern Pyramid frontier. The Lantern Causeway markers preserve
distance-toll glyphs in the same notation format as Eastern Desert charter
stones, a last thread of Keeper-era order before the pyramid's own
jurisdiction begins.

The springs have diminished faster than the Great Oasis's primary vents
since the Ninth Meridian failure. Ground tremors propagate through the
aquifer from the Southern Pyramid's restless depths. Locals attribute them
to the Moon Sovereign stirring in the nadir.
